2765
2766void MacroAssembler::StackOverflowCheck(Register num_args,
2767 Label* stack_overflow) {
2768 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
2769 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
2770 Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
2771
2772 // Check the stack for overflow.
2773 // We are not trying to catch interruptions (e.g. debug break and
2774 // preemption) here, so the "real stack limit" is checked.
2775
2776 LoadStackLimit(scratch, StackLimitKind::kRealStackLimit);
2777 // Make scratch the space we have left. The stack might already be overflowed
2778 // here which will cause scratch to become negative.
2779 Sub(scratch, sp, scratch);
2780 // Check if the arguments will overflow the stack.
2781 Cmp(scratch, Operand(num_args, LSL, kSystemPointerSizeLog2));
2782 B(le, stack_overflow);
2783}
2784
2785void MacroAssembler::InvokePrologue(Register formal_parameter_count,
2786 Register actual_argument_count,
2787 InvokeType type) {
2788 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
2789 // x0: actual arguments count.
2790 // x1: function (passed through to callee).
2791 // x2: expected arguments count.
2792 // x3: new target
2793 Label regular_invoke;
2794 DCHECK_EQ(actual_argument_count, x0);
2795 DCHECK_EQ(formal_parameter_count, x2);
2796
2797 // If overapplication or if the actual argument count is equal to the
2798 // formal parameter count, no need to push extra undefined values.
2799 Register extra_argument_count = x2;
2800 Subs(extra_argument_count, formal_parameter_count, actual_argument_count);
2801 B(le, &regular_invoke);
2802
2803 // The stack pointer in arm64 needs to be 16-byte aligned. We might need to
2804 // (1) add an extra padding or (2) remove (re-use) the extra padding already
2805 // in the stack. Let {slots_to_copy} be the number of slots (arguments) to
2806 // move up in the stack and let {slots_to_claim} be the number of extra stack
2807 // slots to claim.
2808 Label even_extra_count, skip_move;
2809 Register slots_to_copy = x5;
2810 Register slots_to_claim = x6;
2811
2812 Mov(slots_to_copy, actual_argument_count);
2813 Mov(slots_to_claim, extra_argument_count);
2814 Tbz(extra_argument_count, 0, &even_extra_count);
2815
2816 // Calculate {slots_to_claim} when {extra_argument_count} is odd.
2817 // If {actual_argument_count} is even, we need one extra padding slot
2818 // {slots_to_claim = extra_argument_count + 1}.
2819 // If {actual_argument_count} is odd, we know that the
2820 // original arguments will have a padding slot that we can reuse
2821 // {slots_to_claim = extra_argument_count - 1}.
2822 {
2823 Register scratch = x11;
2824 Add(slots_to_claim, extra_argument_count, 1);
2825 And(scratch, actual_argument_count, 1);
2826 Sub(slots_to_claim, slots_to_claim, Operand(scratch, LSL, 1));
2827 }
2828
2829 Bind(&even_extra_count);
2830 Cbz(slots_to_claim, &skip_move);
2831
2832 Label stack_overflow;
2833 StackOverflowCheck(slots_to_claim, &stack_overflow);
2834 Claim(slots_to_claim);
2835
2836 // Move the arguments already in the stack including the receiver.
2837 {
2838 Register src = x7;
2839 Register dst = x8;
2840 SlotAddress(src, slots_to_claim);
2841 SlotAddress(dst, 0);
2842 CopyDoubleWords(dst, src, slots_to_copy);
2843 }
2844
2845 Bind(&skip_move);
2846 Register pointer_next_value = x6;
2847
2848 // Copy extra arguments as undefined values.
2849 {
2850 Label loop;
2851 Register undefined_value = x7;
2852 Register count = x8;
2853 LoadRoot(undefined_value, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
2854 SlotAddress(pointer_next_value, actual_argument_count);
2855 Mov(count, extra_argument_count);
2856 Bind(&loop);
2857 Str(undefined_value,
2858 MemOperand(pointer_next_value, kSystemPointerSize, PostIndex));
2859 Subs(count, count, 1);
2860 Cbnz(count, &loop);
2861 }
2862
2863 // Set padding if needed.
2864 {
2865 Label skip;
2866 Register total_args_slots = x5;
2867 Add(total_args_slots, actual_argument_count, extra_argument_count);
2868 Tbz(total_args_slots, 0, &skip);
2869 Str(padreg, MemOperand(pointer_next_value));
2870 Bind(&skip);
2871 }
2872 B(&regular_invoke);
2873
2874 bind(&stack_overflow);
2875 {
2876 FrameScope frame(
2877 this, has_frame() ? StackFrame::NO_FRAME_TYPE : StackFrame::INTERNAL);
2878 CallRuntime(Runtime::kThrowStackOverflow);
2879 Unreachable();
2880 }
2881
2882 Bind(&regular_invoke);
2883}
2884
2885void MacroAssembler::CallDebugOnFunctionCall(
2886 Register fun, Register new_target,
2887 Register expected_parameter_count_or_dispatch_handle,
2888 Register actual_parameter_count) {
2889 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
2890 DCHECK(!AreAliased(x5, fun, new_target,
2891 expected_parameter_count_or_dispatch_handle,
2892 actual_parameter_count));
2893 // Load receiver to pass it later to DebugOnFunctionCall hook.
2894 Peek(x5, ReceiverOperand());
2895 FrameScope frame(
2896 this, has_frame() ? StackFrame::NO_FRAME_TYPE : StackFrame::INTERNAL);
2897
2898 if (!new_target.is_valid()) new_target = padreg;
2899
2900 // Save values on stack.
2901 SmiTag(expected_parameter_count_or_dispatch_handle);
2902 SmiTag(actual_parameter_count);
2903 Push(expected_parameter_count_or_dispatch_handle, actual_parameter_count,
2904 new_target, fun);
2905 Push(fun, x5);
2906 CallRuntime(Runtime::kDebugOnFunctionCall);
2907
2908 // Restore values from stack.
2909 Pop(fun, new_target, actual_parameter_count,
2910 expected_parameter_count_or_dispatch_handle);
2911 SmiUntag(actual_parameter_count);
2912 SmiUntag(expected_parameter_count_or_dispatch_handle);
2913}

2916void MacroAssembler::InvokeFunction(
2917 Register function, Register actual_parameter_count, InvokeType type,
2918 ArgumentAdaptionMode argument_adaption_mode) {

2920 // You can't call a function without a valid frame.

2924 // (See FullCodeGenerator::Generate().)

2928 LoadTaggedField(cp, FieldMemOperand(function, JSFunction::kContextOffset));
2929

2931 argument_adaption_mode);
2932}

2950void MacroAssembler::InvokeFunctionCode(
2951 Register function, Register new_target, Register actual_parameter_count,
2952 InvokeType type, ArgumentAdaptionMode argument_adaption_mode) {
2953 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
2954 // You can't call a function without a valid frame.
2955 DCHECK_IMPLIES(type == InvokeType::kCall, has_frame());
2956 DCHECK_EQ(function, x1);
2957 DCHECK_IMPLIES(new_target.is_valid(), new_target == x3);
2958
2959 Register dispatch_handle = kJavaScriptCallDispatchHandleRegister;
2960 Ldr(dispatch_handle.W(),
2961 FieldMemOperand(function, JSFunction::kDispatchHandleOffset));
2962
2963 // On function call, call into the debugger if necessary.
2964 Label debug_hook, continue_after_hook;
2965 {
2966 Mov(x5, ExternalReference::debug_hook_on_function_call_address(isolate()));
2967 Ldrsb(x5, MemOperand(x5));
2968 Cbnz(x5, &debug_hook);
2969 }
2970 bind(&continue_after_hook);
2971
2972 // Clear the new.target register if not given.
2973 if (!new_target.is_valid()) {
2974 LoadRoot(x3, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
2975 }
2976
2977 Register scratch = x20;
2978 if (argument_adaption_mode == ArgumentAdaptionMode::kAdapt) {
2979 Register expected_parameter_count = x2;
2980 LoadParameterCountFromJSDispatchTable(expected_parameter_count,
2981 dispatch_handle, scratch);
2982 InvokePrologue(expected_parameter_count, actual_parameter_count, type);
2983 }
2984
2985 // We call indirectly through the code field in the function to
2986 // allow recompilation to take effect without changing any of the
2987 // call sites.
2988 LoadEntrypointFromJSDispatchTable(kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister,
2989 dispatch_handle, scratch);
2990 switch (type) {
2991 case InvokeType::kCall:
2992 Call(kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister);
2993 break;
2994 case InvokeType::kJump:
2995 // We jump through x17 here because for Branch Identification (BTI) we use
2996 // "Call" (`bti c`) rather than "Jump" (`bti j`) landing pads for
2997 // tail-called code. See TailCallBuiltin for more information.
2998 Mov(x17, kJavaScriptCallCodeStartRegister);
2999 Jump(x17);
3000 break;
3001 }
3002 Label done;
3003 B(&done);
3004
3005 // Deferred debug hook.
3006 bind(&debug_hook);
3007 CallDebugOnFunctionCall(function, new_target, dispatch_handle,
3008 actual_parameter_count);
3009 B(&continue_after_hook);
3010
3011 bind(&done);
3012}
3013#else
3014void MacroAssembler::InvokeFunctionCode(Register function, Register new_target,
3015 Register expected_parameter_count,
3016 Register actual_parameter_count,
3017 InvokeType type) {
3018 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3019 // You can't call a function without a valid frame.
3020 DCHECK_IMPLIES(type == InvokeType::kCall, has_frame());
3021 DCHECK_EQ(function, x1);
3022 DCHECK_IMPLIES(new_target.is_valid(), new_target == x3);
3023
3024 // On function call, call into the debugger if necessary.
3025 Label debug_hook, continue_after_hook;
3026 {
3027 Mov(x5, ExternalReference::debug_hook_on_function_call_address(isolate()));
3028 Ldrsb(x5, MemOperand(x5));
3029 Cbnz(x5, &debug_hook);
3030 }
3031 bind(&continue_after_hook);
3032
3033 // Clear the new.target register if not given.
3034 if (!new_target.is_valid()) {
3035 LoadRoot(x3, RootIndex::kUndefinedValue);
3036 }
3037
3038 InvokePrologue(expected_parameter_count, actual_parameter_count, type);
3039
3040 // The called function expects the call kind in x5.
3041 // We call indirectly through the code field in the function to
3042 // allow recompilation to take effect without changing any of the
3043 // call sites.
3044 constexpr int unused_argument_count = 0;
3045 switch (type) {
3046 case InvokeType::kCall:
3047 CallJSFunction(function, unused_argument_count);
3048 break;
3049 case InvokeType::kJump:
3050 JumpJSFunction(function);
3051 break;
3052 }
3053 Label done;
3054 B(&done);
3055
3056 // Deferred debug hook.
3057 bind(&debug_hook);
3058 CallDebugOnFunctionCall(function, new_target, expected_parameter_count,
3059 actual_parameter_count);
3060 B(&continue_after_hook);
3061
3062 bind(&done);
3063}
3064
3065void MacroAssembler::InvokeFunctionWithNewTarget(
3066 Register function, Register new_target, Register actual_parameter_count,
3067 InvokeType type) {
3068 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3069 // You can't call a function without a valid frame.
3070 DCHECK(type == InvokeType::kJump || has_frame());
3071
3072 // Contract with called JS functions requires that function is passed in x1.
3073 // (See FullCodeGenerator::Generate().)
3074 DCHECK_EQ(function, x1);
3075
3076 Register expected_parameter_count = x2;
3077
3078 LoadTaggedField(cp, FieldMemOperand(function, JSFunction::kContextOffset));
3079 // The number of arguments is stored as an int32_t, and -1 is a marker
3080 // (kDontAdaptArgumentsSentinel), so we need sign
3081 // extension to correctly handle it.
3082 LoadTaggedField(
3083 expected_parameter_count,
3084 FieldMemOperand(function, JSFunction::kSharedFunctionInfoOffset));
3085 Ldrh(expected_parameter_count,
3086 FieldMemOperand(expected_parameter_count,
3087 SharedFunctionInfo::kFormalParameterCountOffset));
3088
3089 InvokeFunctionCode(function, new_target, expected_parameter_count,

3093void MacroAssembler::InvokeFunction(Register function,
3094 Register expected_parameter_count,
3095 Register actual_parameter_count,
3096 InvokeType type) {
3097 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3098 // You can't call a function without a valid frame.
3099 DCHECK(type == InvokeType::kJump || has_frame());
3100

3102 // (See FullCodeGenerator::Generate().)

3107
3108 InvokeFunctionCode(function, no_reg, expected_parameter_count,
3109 actual_parameter_count, type);
3110}

3131
3132void MacroAssembler::TryConvertDoubleToInt64(Register result,
3133 DoubleRegister double_input,
3134 Label* done) {
3135 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3136 // Try to convert with an FPU convert instruction. It's trivial to compute
3137 // the modulo operation on an integer register so we convert to a 64-bit
3138 // integer.
3139 //
3140 // Fcvtzs will saturate to INT64_MIN (0x800...00) or INT64_MAX (0x7FF...FF)
3141 // when the double is out of range. NaNs and infinities will be converted to 0
3142 // (as ECMA-262 requires).
3143 Fcvtzs(result.X(), double_input);
3144
3145 // The values INT64_MIN (0x800...00) or INT64_MAX (0x7FF...FF) are not
3146 // representable using a double, so if the result is one of those then we know
3147 // that saturation occurred, and we need to manually handle the conversion.
3148 //
3149 // It is easy to detect INT64_MIN and INT64_MAX because adding or subtracting
3150 // 1 will cause signed overflow.
3151 Cmp(result.X(), 1);
3152 Ccmp(result.X(), -1, VFlag, vc);
3153
3154 B(vc, done);
3155}
3156
3157void MacroAssembler::TruncateDoubleToI(Isolate* isolate, Zone* zone,
3158 Register result,
3159 DoubleRegister double_input,
3160 StubCallMode stub_mode,
3161 LinkRegisterStatus lr_status) {
3162 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3163 if (CpuFeatures::IsSupported(JSCVT)) {
3164 Fjcvtzs(result.W(), double_input);
3165 return;
3166 }
3167
3168 Label done;
3169
3170 // Try to convert the double to an int64. If successful, the bottom 32 bits
3171 // contain our truncated int32 result.
3172 TryConvertDoubleToInt64(result, double_input, &done);
3173
3174 // If we fell through then inline version didn't succeed - call stub instead.
3175 if (lr_status == kLRHasNotBeenSaved) {
3176 Push<MacroAssembler::kSignLR>(lr, double_input);
3177 } else {
3178 Push<MacroAssembler::kDontStoreLR>(xzr, double_input);
3179 }
3180
3181 // DoubleToI preserves any registers it needs to clobber.
3182#if V8_ENABLE_WEBASSEMBLY
3183 if (stub_mode == StubCallMode::kCallWasmRuntimeStub) {
3184 Call(static_cast<Address>(Builtin::kDoubleToI), RelocInfo::WASM_STUB_CALL);
3185#else
3186 // For balance.
3187 if (false) {
3188#endif // V8_ENABLE_WEBASSEMBLY
3189 } else {
3190 CallBuiltin(Builtin::kDoubleToI);
3191 }
3192 Ldr(result, MemOperand(sp, 0));
3193
3194 DCHECK_EQ(xzr.SizeInBytes(), double_input.SizeInBytes());
3195
3196 if (lr_status == kLRHasNotBeenSaved) {
3197 // Pop into xzr here to drop the double input on the stack:
3198 Pop<MacroAssembler::kAuthLR>(xzr, lr);
3199 } else {
3200 Drop(2);
3201 }
3202
3203 Bind(&done);
3204 // Keep our invariant that the upper 32 bits are zero.
3205 Uxtw(result.W(), result.W());
3206}

3208void MacroAssembler::Prologue() {
3209 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3210 Push<MacroAssembler::kSignLR>(lr, fp);
3211 mov(fp, sp);
3212 static_assert(kExtraSlotClaimedByPrologue == 1);
3213 Push(cp, kJSFunctionRegister, kJavaScriptCallArgCountRegister, padreg);
3214}
3215
3216void MacroAssembler::EnterFrame(StackFrame::Type type) {
3217 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
3218
3219 if (StackFrame::IsJavaScript(type)) {
3220 // Just push a minimal "machine frame", saving the frame pointer and return
3221 // address, without any markers.
3222 Push<MacroAssembler::kSignLR>(lr, fp);
3223 Mov(fp, sp);
3224 // sp[1] : lr
3225 // sp[0] : fp
3226 } else {
3227 Register type_reg = temps.AcquireX();
3228 Mov(type_reg, StackFrame::TypeToMarker(type));
3229 Register fourth_reg = padreg;
3230 if (type == StackFrame::CONSTRUCT || type == StackFrame::FAST_CONSTRUCT) {
3231 fourth_reg = cp;
3232 }
3233#if V8_ENABLE_WEBASSEMBLY
3234 if (type == StackFrame::WASM || type == StackFrame::WASM_LIFTOFF_SETUP ||
3235 type == StackFrame::WASM_EXIT) {
3236 fourth_reg = kWasmImplicitArgRegister;
3237 }
3238#endif // V8_ENABLE_WEBASSEMBLY
3239 Push<MacroAssembler::kSignLR>(lr, fp, type_reg, fourth_reg);
3240 static constexpr int kSPToFPDelta = 2 * kSystemPointerSize;
3241 Add(fp, sp, kSPToFPDelta);
3242 // sp[3] : lr
3243 // sp[2] : fp
3244 // sp[1] : type
3245 // sp[0] : cp | wasm instance | for alignment
3246 }
3247}
3248
3249void MacroAssembler::LeaveFrame(StackFrame::Type type) {
3250 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3251 // Drop the execution stack down to the frame pointer and restore
3252 // the caller frame pointer and return address.
3253 Mov(sp, fp);
3254 Pop<MacroAssembler::kAuthLR>(fp, lr);
3255}
3256
3257void MacroAssembler::EnterExitFrame(const Register& scratch, int extra_space,
3258 StackFrame::Type frame_type) {
3259 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3260 DCHECK(frame_type == StackFrame::EXIT ||
3261 frame_type == StackFrame::BUILTIN_EXIT ||
3262 frame_type == StackFrame::API_ACCESSOR_EXIT ||
3263 frame_type == StackFrame::API_CALLBACK_EXIT);
3264
3265 // Set up the new stack frame.
3266 Push<MacroAssembler::kSignLR>(lr, fp);
3267 Mov(fp, sp);
3268 Mov(scratch, StackFrame::TypeToMarker(frame_type));
3269 Push(scratch, xzr);
3270 // fp[8]: CallerPC (lr)
3271 // fp -> fp[0]: CallerFP (old fp)
3272 // fp[-8]: STUB marker
3273 // sp -> fp[-16]: Space reserved for SPOffset.
3274 static_assert((2 * kSystemPointerSize) ==
3275 ExitFrameConstants::kCallerSPOffset);
3276 static_assert((1 * kSystemPointerSize) ==
3277 ExitFrameConstants::kCallerPCOffset);
3278 static_assert((0 * kSystemPointerSize) ==
3279 ExitFrameConstants::kCallerFPOffset);
3280 static_assert((-2 * kSystemPointerSize) == ExitFrameConstants::kSPOffset);
3281
3282 // Save the frame pointer and context pointer in the top frame.
3283 Mov(scratch,
3284 ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kCEntryFPAddress, isolate()));
3285 Str(fp, MemOperand(scratch));
3286 Mov(scratch,
3287 ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kContextAddress, isolate()));
3288 Str(cp, MemOperand(scratch));
3289
3290 static_assert((-2 * kSystemPointerSize) ==
3291 ExitFrameConstants::kLastExitFrameField);
3292
3293 // Round the number of space we need to claim to a multiple of two.
3294 int slots_to_claim = RoundUp(extra_space + 1, 2);
3295
3296 // Reserve space for the return address and for user requested memory.
3297 // We do this before aligning to make sure that we end up correctly
3298 // aligned with the minimum of wasted space.
3299 Claim(slots_to_claim, kXRegSize);
3300 // fp[8]: CallerPC (lr)
3301 // fp -> fp[0]: CallerFP (old fp)
3302 // fp[-8]: STUB marker
3303 // fp[-16]: Space reserved for SPOffset.
3304 // sp[8]: Extra space reserved for caller (if extra_space != 0).
3305 // sp -> sp[0]: Space reserved for the return address.
3306
3307 // ExitFrame::GetStateForFramePointer expects to find the return address at
3308 // the memory address immediately below the pointer stored in SPOffset.
3309 // It is not safe to derive much else from SPOffset, because the size of the
3310 // padding can vary.
3311 Add(scratch, sp, kXRegSize);
3312 Str(scratch, MemOperand(fp, ExitFrameConstants::kSPOffset));
3313}
3314
3315// Leave the current exit frame.
3316void MacroAssembler::LeaveExitFrame(const Register& scratch,
3317 const Register& scratch2) {
3318 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3319
3320 // Restore the context pointer from the top frame.
3321 Mov(scratch,
3322 ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kContextAddress, isolate()));
3323 Ldr(cp, MemOperand(scratch));
3324
3325 if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
3326 // Also emit debug code to clear the cp in the top frame.
3327 Mov(scratch2, Operand(Context::kInvalidContext));
3328 Mov(scratch, ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kContextAddress,
3329 isolate()));
3330 Str(scratch2, MemOperand(scratch));
3331 }
3332 // Clear the frame pointer from the top frame.
3333 Mov(scratch,
3334 ExternalReference::Create(IsolateAddressId::kCEntryFPAddress, isolate()));
3335 Str(xzr, MemOperand(scratch));
3336
3337 // Pop the exit frame.
3338 // fp[8]: CallerPC (lr)
3339 // fp -> fp[0]: CallerFP (old fp)
3340 // fp[...]: The rest of the frame.
3341 Mov(sp, fp);
3342 Pop<MacroAssembler::kAuthLR>(fp, lr);
3343}

3383void MacroAssembler::JumpIfJSAnyIsNotPrimitive(Register heap_object,
3384 Register scratch, Label* target,
3385 Label::Distance distance,
3386 Condition cc) {
3387 CHECK(cc == Condition::kUnsignedLessThan ||
3388 cc == Condition::kUnsignedGreaterThanEqual);
3389 if (V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL) {
3390#ifdef DEBUG
3391 Label ok;
3392 LoadMap(scratch, heap_object);
3393 CompareInstanceTypeRange(scratch, scratch, FIRST_JS_RECEIVER_TYPE,
3394 LAST_JS_RECEIVER_TYPE);
3395 B(Condition::kUnsignedLessThanEqual, &ok);
3396 LoadMap(scratch, heap_object);
3397 CompareInstanceTypeRange(scratch, scratch, FIRST_PRIMITIVE_HEAP_OBJECT_TYPE,
3398 LAST_PRIMITIVE_HEAP_OBJECT_TYPE);
3399 B(Condition::kUnsignedLessThanEqual, &ok);
3400 Abort(AbortReason::kInvalidReceiver);
3401 bind(&ok);
3402#endif // DEBUG
3403
3404 // All primitive object's maps are allocated at the start of the read only
3405 // heap. Thus JS_RECEIVER's must have maps with larger (compressed)
3406 // addresses.
3407 LoadCompressedMap(scratch, heap_object);
3408 CmpTagged(scratch, Immediate(InstanceTypeChecker::kNonJsReceiverMapLimit));
3409 } else {
3410 static_assert(LAST_JS_RECEIVER_TYPE == LAST_TYPE);
3411 CompareObjectType(heap_object, scratch, scratch, FIRST_JS_RECEIVER_TYPE);
3412 }
3413 B(cc, target);
3414}

3690 if (COMPRESS_POINTERS_BOOL) {
3691 Stlr(value.W(), temp);
3692 } else {
3693 Stlr(value, temp);
3694 }
3695}

3776void MacroAssembler::CheckPageFlag(const Register& object, int mask,
3777 Condition cc, Label* condition_met) {
3778 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);

3780 Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
3781 And(scratch, object, ~MemoryChunk::GetAlignmentMaskForAssembler());

3784 TestAndBranchIfAnySet(scratch, mask, condition_met);
3785 } else {

3808
3809void MacroAssembler::RecordWriteField(
3810 Register object, int offset, Register value, LinkRegisterStatus lr_status,
3811 SaveFPRegsMode save_fp, SmiCheck smi_check, ReadOnlyCheck ro_check,
3812 SlotDescriptor slot) {
3813 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3814 DCHECK(!AreAliased(object, value));
3815 // First, check if a write barrier is even needed. The tests below
3816 // catch stores of Smis and read-only objects.
3817 Label done;
3818
3819#if V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL
3820 if (ro_check == ReadOnlyCheck::kInline) {
3821 // Quick check for Read-only and small Smi values.
3822 static_assert(StaticReadOnlyRoot::kLastAllocatedRoot < kRegularPageSize);
3823 JumpIfUnsignedLessThan(value, kRegularPageSize, &done);
3824 }
3825#endif // V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL
3826
3827 // Skip the barrier if writing a smi.
3828 if (smi_check == SmiCheck::kInline) {
3829 JumpIfSmi(value, &done);
3830 }
3831
3832 // Although the object register is tagged, the offset is relative to the start
3833 // of the object, so offset must be a multiple of kTaggedSize.
3834 DCHECK(IsAligned(offset, kTaggedSize));
3835
3836 if (v8_flags.slow_debug_code) {
3837 ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(this, "Verify slot_address");
3838 Label ok;
3839 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
3840 Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
3841 DCHECK(!AreAliased(object, value, scratch));
3842 Add(scratch, object, offset - kHeapObjectTag);
3843 Tst(scratch, kTaggedSize - 1);
3844 B(eq, &ok);
3845 Abort(AbortReason::kUnalignedCellInWriteBarrier);
3846 Bind(&ok);
3847 }
3848
3849 RecordWrite(object, Operand(offset - kHeapObjectTag), value, lr_status,
3850 save_fp, SmiCheck::kOmit, ReadOnlyCheck::kOmit, slot);
3851
3852 Bind(&done);
3853}

3890void MacroAssembler::LoadExternalPointerField(Register destination,
3891 MemOperand field_operand,
3892 ExternalPointerTagRange tag_range,
3893 Register isolate_root) {
3894 DCHECK(!AreAliased(destination, isolate_root));
3895 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
3896#ifdef V8_ENABLE_SANDBOX
3897 DCHECK(!tag_range.IsEmpty());
3898 DCHECK(!IsSharedExternalPointerType(tag_range));
3899 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
3900 Register external_table = temps.AcquireX();
3901 if (isolate_root == no_reg) {
3902 DCHECK(root_array_available_);
3903 isolate_root = kRootRegister;
3904 }
3905 Ldr(external_table,
3906 MemOperand(isolate_root,
3907 IsolateData::external_pointer_table_offset() +
3908 Internals::kExternalPointerTableBasePointerOffset));
3909 Ldr(destination.W(), field_operand);
3910 Mov(destination, Operand(destination, LSR, kExternalPointerIndexShift));
3911 Ldr(destination, MemOperand(external_table, destination, LSL,
3912 kExternalPointerTableEntrySizeLog2));
3913
3914 // We don't expect to see empty fields here. If this is ever needed, consider
3915 // using an dedicated empty value entry for those tags instead (i.e. an entry
3916 // with the right tag and nullptr payload).
3917 DCHECK(!ExternalPointerCanBeEmpty(tag_range));
3918
3919 // We need another scratch register for the 64-bit tag constant. Instead of
3920 // forcing the `And` to allocate a new temp register (which we may not have),
3921 // reuse the temp register that we used for the external pointer table base.
3922 Register scratch = external_table;
3923 if (tag_range.Size() == 1) {
3924 // The common and simple case: we expect exactly one tag.
3925 static_assert(kExternalPointerShiftedTagMask == 0x7f);
3926 Ubfx(scratch, destination, kExternalPointerTagShift, 7);
3927 Cmp(scratch, Immediate(tag_range.first));
3928 SbxCheck(eq, AbortReason::kExternalPointerTagMismatch);
3929 And(destination, destination, Immediate(kExternalPointerPayloadMask));
3930 } else {
3931 // Not currently supported. Implement once needed.
3932 DCHECK_NE(tag_range, kAnyExternalPointerTagRange);
3933 UNREACHABLE();
3934 }
3935#else
3936 Ldr(destination, field_operand);
3937#endif // V8_ENABLE_SANDBOX
3938}

3988#ifdef V8_ENABLE_SANDBOX
3989void MacroAssembler::ResolveIndirectPointerHandle(Register destination,
3990 Register handle,
3991 IndirectPointerTag tag) {
3992 // The tag implies which pointer table to use.
3993 if (tag == kUnknownIndirectPointerTag) {
3994 // In this case we have to rely on the handle marking to determine which
3995 // pointer table to use.
3996 Label is_trusted_pointer_handle, done;
3997 constexpr int kCodePointerHandleMarkerBit = 0;
3998 static_assert((1 << kCodePointerHandleMarkerBit) ==
3999 kCodePointerHandleMarker);
4000 Tbz(handle, kCodePointerHandleMarkerBit, &is_trusted_pointer_handle);
4001 ResolveCodePointerHandle(destination, handle);
4002 B(&done);
4003 Bind(&is_trusted_pointer_handle);
4004 ResolveTrustedPointerHandle(destination, handle,
4005 kUnknownIndirectPointerTag);
4006 Bind(&done);
4007 } else if (tag == kCodeIndirectPointerTag) {
4008 ResolveCodePointerHandle(destination, handle);
4009 } else {
4010 ResolveTrustedPointerHandle(destination, handle, tag);
4011 }
4012}
4013
4014void MacroAssembler::ResolveTrustedPointerHandle(Register destination,
4015 Register handle,
4016 IndirectPointerTag tag) {
4017 DCHECK_NE(tag, kCodeIndirectPointerTag);
4018 DCHECK(!AreAliased(handle, destination));
4019
4020 Register table = destination;
4021 DCHECK(root_array_available_);
4022 Ldr(table,
4023 MemOperand{kRootRegister, IsolateData::trusted_pointer_table_offset()});
4024 Mov(handle, Operand(handle, LSR, kTrustedPointerHandleShift));
4025 Ldr(destination,
4026 MemOperand(table, handle, LSL, kTrustedPointerTableEntrySizeLog2));
4027 // Untag the pointer and remove the marking bit in one operation.
4028 Register tag_reg = handle;
4029 Mov(tag_reg, Immediate(~(tag | kTrustedPointerTableMarkBit)));
4030 And(destination, destination, tag_reg);
4031}
4032
4033void MacroAssembler::ResolveCodePointerHandle(Register destination,
4034 Register handle) {
4035 DCHECK(!AreAliased(handle, destination));
4036
4037 Register table = destination;
4038 Mov(table, ExternalReference::code_pointer_table_address());
4039 Mov(handle, Operand(handle, LSR, kCodePointerHandleShift));
4040 Add(destination, table, Operand(handle, LSL, kCodePointerTableEntrySizeLog2));
4041 Ldr(destination,
4042 MemOperand(destination,
4043 Immediate(kCodePointerTableEntryCodeObjectOffset)));
4044 // The LSB is used as marking bit by the code pointer table, so here we have
4045 // to set it using a bitwise OR as it may or may not be set.
4046 Orr(destination, destination, Immediate(kHeapObjectTag));
4047}

4049void MacroAssembler::LoadCodeEntrypointViaCodePointer(Register destination,
4050 MemOperand field_operand,
4051 CodeEntrypointTag tag) {
4052 DCHECK_NE(tag, kInvalidEntrypointTag);
4053 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4054 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4055 Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
4056 Mov(scratch, ExternalReference::code_pointer_table_address());
4057 Ldr(destination.W(), field_operand);
4058 // TODO(saelo): can the offset computation be done more efficiently?
4059 Mov(destination, Operand(destination, LSR, kCodePointerHandleShift));
4060 Mov(destination, Operand(destination, LSL, kCodePointerTableEntrySizeLog2));
4061 Ldr(destination, MemOperand(scratch, destination));
4062 if (tag != 0) {
4063 Mov(scratch, Immediate(tag));
4064 Eor(destination, destination, scratch);
4065 }
4066}

4230
4231void MacroAssembler::MoveObjectAndSlot(Register dst_object, Register dst_slot,
4232 Register object, Operand offset) {
4233 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4234 DCHECK_NE(dst_object, dst_slot);
4235 // If `offset` is a register, it cannot overlap with `object`.
4236 DCHECK_IMPLIES(!offset.IsImmediate(), offset.reg() != object);
4237
4238 // If the slot register does not overlap with the object register, we can
4239 // overwrite it.
4240 if (dst_slot != object) {
4241 Add(dst_slot, object, offset);
4242 Mov(dst_object, object);
4243 return;
4244 }
4245
4246 DCHECK_EQ(dst_slot, object);
4247
4248 // If the destination object register does not overlap with the offset
4249 // register, we can overwrite it.
4250 if (offset.IsImmediate() || (offset.reg() != dst_object)) {
4251 Mov(dst_object, dst_slot);
4252 Add(dst_slot, dst_slot, offset);
4253 return;
4254 }
4255
4256 DCHECK_EQ(dst_object, offset.reg());
4257
4258 // We only have `dst_slot` and `dst_object` left as distinct registers so we
4259 // have to swap them. We write this as a add+sub sequence to avoid using a
4260 // scratch register.
4261 Add(dst_slot, dst_slot, dst_object);
4262 Sub(dst_object, dst_slot, dst_object);
4263}
4264
4265// If lr_status is kLRHasBeenSaved, lr will be clobbered.
4266//
4267// The register 'object' contains a heap object pointer. The heap object tag is
4268// shifted away.
4269void MacroAssembler::RecordWrite(Register object, Operand offset,
4270 Register value, LinkRegisterStatus lr_status,
4271 SaveFPRegsMode fp_mode, SmiCheck smi_check,
4272 ReadOnlyCheck ro_check, SlotDescriptor slot) {
4273 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4274 ASM_LOCATION_IN_ASSEMBLER("MacroAssembler::RecordWrite");
4275 DCHECK(!AreAliased(object, value));
4276
4277 if (v8_flags.slow_debug_code) {
4278 ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(this, "Verify slot_address");
4279 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4280 Register temp = temps.AcquireX();
4281 DCHECK(!AreAliased(object, value, temp));
4282 Add(temp, object, offset);
4283 if (slot.contains_indirect_pointer()) {
4284 LoadIndirectPointerField(temp, MemOperand(temp),
4285 slot.indirect_pointer_tag());
4286 } else {
4287 DCHECK(slot.contains_direct_pointer());
4288 LoadTaggedField(temp, MemOperand(temp));
4289 }
4290 Cmp(temp, value);
4291 Check(eq, AbortReason::kWrongAddressOrValuePassedToRecordWrite);
4292 }
4293
4294 if (v8_flags.disable_write_barriers) {
4295 return;
4296 }
4297
4298 // First, check if a write barrier is even needed. The tests below
4299 // catch stores of smisand read-only objects, as well as stores into the
4300 // young generation.
4301 Label done;
4302
4303#if V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL
4304 if (ro_check == ReadOnlyCheck::kInline) {
4305 // Quick check for Read-only and small Smi values.
4306 static_assert(StaticReadOnlyRoot::kLastAllocatedRoot < kRegularPageSize);
4307 JumpIfUnsignedLessThan(value, kRegularPageSize, &done);
4308 }
4309#endif // V8_STATIC_ROOTS_BOOL
4310
4311 if (smi_check == SmiCheck::kInline) {
4312 DCHECK_EQ(0, kSmiTag);
4313 JumpIfSmi(value, &done);
4314 }
4315
4316 if (slot.contains_indirect_pointer()) {
4317 // The indirect pointer write barrier is only enabled during marking.
4318 JumpIfNotMarking(&done);
4319 } else {
4320 CheckPageFlag(value, MemoryChunk::kPointersToHereAreInterestingMask, eq,
4321 &done);
4322
4323 CheckPageFlag(object, MemoryChunk::kPointersFromHereAreInterestingMask, eq,
4324 &done);
4325 }
4326
4327 // Record the actual write.
4328 if (lr_status == kLRHasNotBeenSaved) {
4329 Push<MacroAssembler::kSignLR>(padreg, lr);
4330 }
4331 Register slot_address = WriteBarrierDescriptor::SlotAddressRegister();
4332 DCHECK(!AreAliased(object, slot_address, value));
4333 if (slot.contains_direct_pointer()) {
4334 // TODO(cbruni): Turn offset into int.
4335 DCHECK(offset.IsImmediate());
4336 Add(slot_address, object, offset);
4337 CallRecordWriteStub(object, slot_address, fp_mode,
4338 StubCallMode::kCallBuiltinPointer);
4339 } else {
4340 DCHECK(slot.contains_indirect_pointer());
4341 CallIndirectPointerBarrier(object, offset, fp_mode,
4342 slot.indirect_pointer_tag());
4343 }
4344 if (lr_status == kLRHasNotBeenSaved) {
4345 Pop<MacroAssembler::kAuthLR>(lr, padreg);
4346 }
4347 if (v8_flags.slow_debug_code) Mov(slot_address, Operand(kZapValue));
4348
4349 Bind(&done);
4350}

4352void MacroAssembler::Check(Condition cond, AbortReason reason) {
4353 Label ok;
4354 B(cond, &ok);
4355 Abort(reason);
4356 // Will not return here.
4357 Bind(&ok);
4358}

4365void MacroAssembler::DebugBreak() { Debug("DebugBreak", 0, BREAK); }
4366
4367void MacroAssembler::Abort(AbortReason reason) {
4368 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4369 if (v8_flags.code_comments) {
4370 RecordComment("Abort message: ");
4371 RecordComment(GetAbortReason(reason));
4372 }
4373
4374 // Avoid emitting call to builtin if requested.
4375 if (trap_on_abort()) {
4376 Brk(0);
4377 return;
4378 }
4379
4380 // We need some scratch registers for the MacroAssembler, so make sure we have
4381 // some. This is safe here because Abort never returns.
4382 uint64_t old_tmp_list = TmpList()->bits();
4383 TmpList()->Combine(MacroAssembler::DefaultTmpList());
4384
4385 if (should_abort_hard()) {
4386 // We don't care if we constructed a frame. Just pretend we did.
4387 FrameScope assume_frame(this, StackFrame::NO_FRAME_TYPE);
4388 Mov(w0, static_cast<int>(reason));
4389 Call(ExternalReference::abort_with_reason());
4390 return;
4391 }
4392
4393 // Avoid infinite recursion; Push contains some assertions that use Abort.
4394 HardAbortScope hard_aborts(this);
4395
4396 Mov(x1, Smi::FromInt(static_cast<int>(reason)));
4397
4398 {
4399 // We don't actually want to generate a pile of code for this, so just
4400 // claim there is a stack frame, without generating one.
4401 FrameScope scope(this, StackFrame::NO_FRAME_TYPE);
4402 if (root_array_available()) {
4403 // Generate an indirect call via builtins entry table here in order to
4404 // ensure that the interpreter_entry_return_pc_offset is the same for
4405 // InterpreterEntryTrampoline and InterpreterEntryTrampolineForProfiling
4406 // when v8_flags.debug_code is enabled.
4407 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4408 Register scratch = temps.AcquireX();
4409 LoadEntryFromBuiltin(Builtin::kAbort, scratch);
4410 Call(scratch);
4411 } else {
4412 CallBuiltin(Builtin::kAbort);
4413 }
4414 }
4415
4416 TmpList()->set_bits(old_tmp_list);
4417}

4420 LoadMap(dst, cp);
4421 LoadTaggedField(
4422 dst, FieldMemOperand(
4423 dst, Map::kConstructorOrBackPointerOrNativeContextOffset));
4424 LoadTaggedField(dst, MemOperand(dst, Context::SlotOffset(index)));

4426
4427void MacroAssembler::TryLoadOptimizedOsrCode(Register scratch_and_result,
4428 CodeKind min_opt_level,
4429 Register feedback_vector,
4430 FeedbackSlot slot,
4431 Label* on_result,
4432 Label::Distance) {
4433 Label fallthrough, clear_slot;
4434 LoadTaggedField(
4435 scratch_and_result,
4436 FieldMemOperand(feedback_vector,
4437 FeedbackVector::OffsetOfElementAt(slot.ToInt())));
4438 LoadWeakValue(scratch_and_result, scratch_and_result, &fallthrough);
4439
4440 // Is it marked_for_deoptimization? If yes, clear the slot.
4441 {
4442 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4443
4444 // The entry references a CodeWrapper object. Unwrap it now.
4445 LoadCodePointerField(
4446 scratch_and_result,
4447 FieldMemOperand(scratch_and_result, CodeWrapper::kCodeOffset));
4448
4449 Register temp = temps.AcquireX();
4450 JumpIfCodeIsMarkedForDeoptimization(scratch_and_result, temp, &clear_slot);
4451 if (min_opt_level == CodeKind::TURBOFAN_JS) {
4452 JumpIfCodeIsTurbofanned(scratch_and_result, temp, on_result);
4453 B(&fallthrough);
4454 } else {
4455 B(on_result);
4456 }
4457 }
4458
4459 bind(&clear_slot);
4460 Mov(scratch_and_result, ClearedValue());
4461 StoreTaggedField(
4462 scratch_and_result,
4463 FieldMemOperand(feedback_vector,
4464 FeedbackVector::OffsetOfElementAt(slot.ToInt())));
4465
4466 bind(&fallthrough);
4467 Mov(scratch_and_result, 0);
4468}

4470// This is the main Printf implementation. All other Printf variants call
4471// PrintfNoPreserve after setting up one or more PreserveRegisterScopes.
4472void MacroAssembler::PrintfNoPreserve(const char* format,
4473 const CPURegister& arg0,
4474 const CPURegister& arg1,
4475 const CPURegister& arg2,
4476 const CPURegister& arg3) {
4477 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4478 // We cannot handle a caller-saved stack pointer. It doesn't make much sense
4479 // in most cases anyway, so this restriction shouldn't be too serious.
4480 DCHECK(!kCallerSaved.IncludesAliasOf(sp));
4481
4482 // The provided arguments, and their proper procedure-call standard registers.
4483 CPURegister args[kPrintfMaxArgCount] = {arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3};
4484 CPURegister pcs[kPrintfMaxArgCount] = {NoReg, NoReg, NoReg, NoReg};
4485
4486 int arg_count = kPrintfMaxArgCount;
4487
4488 // The PCS varargs registers for printf. Note that x0 is used for the printf
4489 // format string.
4490 static const CPURegList kPCSVarargs =
4491 CPURegList(CPURegister::kRegister, kXRegSizeInBits, 1, arg_count);
4492 static const CPURegList kPCSVarargsFP =
4493 CPURegList(CPURegister::kVRegister, kDRegSizeInBits, 0, arg_count - 1);
4494
4495 // We can use caller-saved registers as scratch values, except for the
4496 // arguments and the PCS registers where they might need to go.
4497 CPURegList tmp_list = kCallerSaved;
4498 tmp_list.Remove(x0); // Used to pass the format string.
4499 tmp_list.Remove(kPCSVarargs);
4500 tmp_list.Remove(arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3);
4501
4502 CPURegList fp_tmp_list = kCallerSavedV;
4503 fp_tmp_list.Remove(kPCSVarargsFP);
4504 fp_tmp_list.Remove(arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3);
4505
4506 // Override the MacroAssembler's scratch register list. The lists will be
4507 // reset automatically at the end of the UseScratchRegisterScope.
4508 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4509 TmpList()->set_bits(tmp_list.bits());
4510 FPTmpList()->set_bits(fp_tmp_list.bits());
4511
4512 // Copies of the printf vararg registers that we can pop from.
4513 CPURegList pcs_varargs = kPCSVarargs;
4514#ifndef V8_OS_WIN
4515 CPURegList pcs_varargs_fp = kPCSVarargsFP;
4516#endif
4517
4518 // Place the arguments. There are lots of clever tricks and optimizations we
4519 // could use here, but Printf is a debug tool so instead we just try to keep
4520 // it simple: Move each input that isn't already in the right place to a
4521 // scratch register, then move everything back.
4522 for (unsigned i = 0; i < kPrintfMaxArgCount; i++) {
4523 // Work out the proper PCS register for this argument.
4524 if (args[i].IsRegister()) {
4525 pcs[i] = pcs_varargs.PopLowestIndex().X();
4526 // We might only need a W register here. We need to know the size of the
4527 // argument so we can properly encode it for the simulator call.
4528 if (args[i].Is32Bits()) pcs[i] = pcs[i].W();
4529 } else if (args[i].IsVRegister()) {
4530 // In C, floats are always cast to doubles for varargs calls.
4531#ifdef V8_OS_WIN
4532 // In case of variadic functions SIMD and Floating-point registers
4533 // aren't used. The general x0-x7 should be used instead.
4534 // https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/cpp/build/arm64-windows-abi-conventions
4535 pcs[i] = pcs_varargs.PopLowestIndex().X();
4536#else
4537 pcs[i] = pcs_varargs_fp.PopLowestIndex().D();
4538#endif
4539 } else {
4540 DCHECK(args[i].IsNone());
4541 arg_count = i;
4542 break;
4543 }
4544
4545 // If the argument is already in the right place, leave it where it is.
4546 if (args[i].Aliases(pcs[i])) continue;
4547
4548 // Otherwise, if the argument is in a PCS argument register, allocate an
4549 // appropriate scratch register and then move it out of the way.
4550 if (kPCSVarargs.IncludesAliasOf(args[i]) ||
4551 kPCSVarargsFP.IncludesAliasOf(args[i])) {
4552 if (args[i].IsRegister()) {
4553 Register old_arg = args[i].Reg();
4554 Register new_arg = temps.AcquireSameSizeAs(old_arg);
4555 Mov(new_arg, old_arg);
4556 args[i] = new_arg;
4557 } else {
4558 VRegister old_arg = args[i].VReg();
4559 VRegister new_arg = temps.AcquireSameSizeAs(old_arg);
4560 Fmov(new_arg, old_arg);
4561 args[i] = new_arg;
4562 }
4563 }
4564 }
4565
4566 // Do a second pass to move values into their final positions and perform any
4567 // conversions that may be required.
4568 for (int i = 0; i < arg_count; i++) {
4569#ifdef V8_OS_WIN
4570 if (args[i].IsVRegister()) {
4571 if (pcs[i].SizeInBytes() != args[i].SizeInBytes()) {
4572 // If the argument is half- or single-precision
4573 // converts to double-precision before that is
4574 // moved into the one of X scratch register.
4575 VRegister temp0 = temps.AcquireD();
4576 Fcvt(temp0.VReg(), args[i].VReg());
4577 Fmov(pcs[i].Reg(), temp0);
4578 } else {
4579 Fmov(pcs[i].Reg(), args[i].VReg());
4580 }
4581 } else {
4582 Mov(pcs[i].Reg(), args[i].Reg(), kDiscardForSameWReg);
4583 }
4584#else
4585 DCHECK(pcs[i].type() == args[i].type());
4586 if (pcs[i].IsRegister()) {
4587 Mov(pcs[i].Reg(), args[i].Reg(), kDiscardForSameWReg);
4588 } else {
4589 DCHECK(pcs[i].IsVRegister());
4590 if (pcs[i].SizeInBytes() == args[i].SizeInBytes()) {
4591 Fmov(pcs[i].VReg(), args[i].VReg());
4592 } else {
4593 Fcvt(pcs[i].VReg(), args[i].VReg());
4594 }
4595 }
4596#endif
4597 }
4598
4599 // Load the format string into x0, as per the procedure-call standard.
4600 //
4601 // To make the code as portable as possible, the format string is encoded
4602 // directly in the instruction stream. It might be cleaner to encode it in a
4603 // literal pool, but since Printf is usually used for debugging, it is
4604 // beneficial for it to be minimally dependent on other features.
4605 Label format_address;
4606 Adr(x0, &format_address);
4607
4608 // Emit the format string directly in the instruction stream.
4609 {
4610 BlockPoolsScope scope(this);
4611 Label after_data;
4612 B(&after_data);
4613 Bind(&format_address);
4614 EmitStringData(format);
4615 Unreachable();
4616 Bind(&after_data);
4617 }
4618
4619 CallPrintf(arg_count, pcs);
4620}
4621
4622void MacroAssembler::CallPrintf(int arg_count, const CPURegister* args) {
4623 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4624 // A call to printf needs special handling for the simulator, since the system
4625 // printf function will use a different instruction set and the procedure-call
4626 // standard will not be compatible.
4627 if (options().enable_simulator_code) {
4628 InstructionAccurateScope scope(this, kPrintfLength / kInstrSize);
4629 hlt(kImmExceptionIsPrintf);
4630 dc32(arg_count); // kPrintfArgCountOffset
4631
4632 // Determine the argument pattern.
4633 uint32_t arg_pattern_list = 0;
4634 for (int i = 0; i < arg_count; i++) {
4635 uint32_t arg_pattern;
4636 if (args[i].IsRegister()) {
4637 arg_pattern = args[i].Is32Bits() ? kPrintfArgW : kPrintfArgX;
4638 } else {
4639 DCHECK(args[i].Is64Bits());
4640 arg_pattern = kPrintfArgD;
4641 }
4642 DCHECK(arg_pattern < (1 << kPrintfArgPatternBits));
4643 arg_pattern_list |= (arg_pattern << (kPrintfArgPatternBits * i));
4644 }
4645 dc32(arg_pattern_list); // kPrintfArgPatternListOffset
4646 return;
4647 }
4648
4649 Call(ExternalReference::printf_function());
4650}
4651
4652void MacroAssembler::Printf(const char* format, CPURegister arg0,
4653 CPURegister arg1, CPURegister arg2,
4654 CPURegister arg3) {
4655 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4656 // Printf is expected to preserve all registers, so make sure that none are
4657 // available as scratch registers until we've preserved them.
4658 uint64_t old_tmp_list = TmpList()->bits();
4659 uint64_t old_fp_tmp_list = FPTmpList()->bits();
4660 TmpList()->set_bits(0);
4661 FPTmpList()->set_bits(0);
4662
4663 CPURegList saved_registers = kCallerSaved;
4664 saved_registers.Align();
4665
4666 // Preserve all caller-saved registers as well as NZCV.
4667 // PushCPURegList asserts that the size of each list is a multiple of 16
4668 // bytes.
4669 PushCPURegList(saved_registers);
4670 PushCPURegList(kCallerSavedV);
4671
4672 // We can use caller-saved registers as scratch values (except for argN).
4673 CPURegList tmp_list = saved_registers;
4674 CPURegList fp_tmp_list = kCallerSavedV;
4675 tmp_list.Remove(arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3);
4676 fp_tmp_list.Remove(arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3);
4677 TmpList()->set_bits(tmp_list.bits());
4678 FPTmpList()->set_bits(fp_tmp_list.bits());
4679
4680 {
4681 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4682 // If any of the arguments are the current stack pointer, allocate a new
4683 // register for them, and adjust the value to compensate for pushing the
4684 // caller-saved registers.
4685 bool arg0_sp = arg0.is_valid() && sp.Aliases(arg0);
4686 bool arg1_sp = arg1.is_valid() && sp.Aliases(arg1);
4687 bool arg2_sp = arg2.is_valid() && sp.Aliases(arg2);
4688 bool arg3_sp = arg3.is_valid() && sp.Aliases(arg3);
4689 if (arg0_sp || arg1_sp || arg2_sp || arg3_sp) {
4690 // Allocate a register to hold the original stack pointer value, to pass
4691 // to PrintfNoPreserve as an argument.
4692 Register arg_sp = temps.AcquireX();
4693 Add(arg_sp, sp,
4694 saved_registers.TotalSizeInBytes() +
4695 kCallerSavedV.TotalSizeInBytes());
4696 if (arg0_sp) arg0 = Register::Create(arg_sp.code(), arg0.SizeInBits());
4697 if (arg1_sp) arg1 = Register::Create(arg_sp.code(), arg1.SizeInBits());
4698 if (arg2_sp) arg2 = Register::Create(arg_sp.code(), arg2.SizeInBits());
4699 if (arg3_sp) arg3 = Register::Create(arg_sp.code(), arg3.SizeInBits());
4700 }
4701
4702 // Preserve NZCV.
4703 {
4704 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4705 Register tmp = temps.AcquireX();
4706 Mrs(tmp, NZCV);
4707 Push(tmp, xzr);
4708 }
4709
4710 PrintfNoPreserve(format, arg0, arg1, arg2, arg3);
4711
4712 // Restore NZCV.
4713 {
4714 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4715 Register tmp = temps.AcquireX();
4716 Pop(xzr, tmp);
4717 Msr(NZCV, tmp);
4718 }
4719 }
4720
4721 PopCPURegList(kCallerSavedV);
4722 PopCPURegList(saved_registers);
4723
4724 TmpList()->set_bits(old_tmp_list);
4725 FPTmpList()->set_bits(old_fp_tmp_list);
4726}

4735 StandardFrameConstants::kCallerPCOffset,

4764void MacroAssembler::PopcntHelper(Register dst, Register src) {
4765 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4766 VRegister scratch = temps.AcquireV(kFormat8B);
4767 VRegister tmp = src.Is32Bits() ? scratch.S() : scratch.D();
4768 Fmov(tmp, src);
4769 Cnt(scratch, scratch);
4770 Addv(scratch.B(), scratch);
4771 Fmov(dst, tmp);
4772}
4773
4774void MacroAssembler::I8x16BitMask(Register dst, VRegister src, VRegister temp) {
4775 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4776 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4777 VRegister tmp = temps.AcquireQ();
4778 VRegister mask = temps.AcquireQ();
4779
4780 if (CpuFeatures::IsSupported(PMULL1Q) && temp.is_valid()) {
4781 CpuFeatureScope scope(this, PMULL1Q);
4782
4783 Movi(mask.V2D(), 0x0102'0408'1020'4080);
4784 // Normalize the input - at most 1 bit per vector element should be set.
4785 Ushr(tmp.V16B(), src.V16B(), 7);
4786 // Collect the input bits into a byte of the output - once for each
4787 // half of the input.
4788 Pmull2(temp.V1Q(), mask.V2D(), tmp.V2D());
4789 Pmull(tmp.V1Q(), mask.V1D(), tmp.V1D());
4790 // Combine the bits from both input halves.
4791 Trn2(tmp.V8B(), tmp.V8B(), temp.V8B());
4792 Mov(dst.W(), tmp.V8H(), 3);
4793 } else {
4794 // Set i-th bit of each lane i. When AND with tmp, the lanes that
4795 // are signed will have i-th bit set, unsigned will be 0.
4796 Sshr(tmp.V16B(), src.V16B(), 7);
4797 Movi(mask.V2D(), 0x8040'2010'0804'0201);
4798 And(tmp.V16B(), mask.V16B(), tmp.V16B());
4799 Ext(mask.V16B(), tmp.V16B(), tmp.V16B(), 8);
4800 Zip1(tmp.V16B(), tmp.V16B(), mask.V16B());
4801 Addv(tmp.H(), tmp.V8H());
4802 Mov(dst.W(), tmp.V8H(), 0);
4803 }
4804}
4805
4806void MacroAssembler::I16x8BitMask(Register dst, VRegister src) {
4807 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4808 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4809 VRegister tmp = temps.AcquireQ();
4810 VRegister mask = temps.AcquireQ();
4811
4812 if (CpuFeatures::IsSupported(PMULL1Q)) {
4813 CpuFeatureScope scope(this, PMULL1Q);
4814
4815 // Normalize the input - at most 1 bit per vector element should be set.
4816 Ushr(tmp.V8H(), src.V8H(), 15);
4817 Movi(mask.V1D(), 0x0102'0408'1020'4080);
4818 // Trim some of the redundant 0 bits, so that we can operate on
4819 // only 64 bits.
4820 Xtn(tmp.V8B(), tmp.V8H());
4821 // Collect the input bits into a byte of the output.
4822 Pmull(tmp.V1Q(), tmp.V1D(), mask.V1D());
4823 Mov(dst.W(), tmp.V16B(), 7);
4824 } else {
4825 Sshr(tmp.V8H(), src.V8H(), 15);
4826 // Set i-th bit of each lane i. When AND with tmp, the lanes that
4827 // are signed will have i-th bit set, unsigned will be 0.
4828 Movi(mask.V2D(), 0x0080'0040'0020'0010, 0x0008'0004'0002'0001);
4829 And(tmp.V16B(), mask.V16B(), tmp.V16B());
4830 Addv(tmp.H(), tmp.V8H());
4831 Mov(dst.W(), tmp.V8H(), 0);
4832 }
4833}
4834
4835void MacroAssembler::I32x4BitMask(Register dst, VRegister src) {
4836 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4837 UseScratchRegisterScope temps(this);
4838 Register tmp = temps.AcquireX();
4839 Mov(dst.X(), src.D(), 1);
4840 Fmov(tmp.X(), src.D());
4841 And(dst.X(), dst.X(), 0x80000000'80000000);
4842 And(tmp.X(), tmp.X(), 0x80000000'80000000);
4843 Orr(dst.X(), dst.X(), Operand(dst.X(), LSL, 31));
4844 Orr(tmp.X(), tmp.X(), Operand(tmp.X(), LSL, 31));
4845 Lsr(dst.X(), dst.X(), 60);
4846 Bfxil(dst.X(), tmp.X(), 62, 2);
4847}
4848
4849void MacroAssembler::I64x2BitMask(Register dst, VRegister src) {
4850 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4851 UseScratchRegisterScope scope(this);
4852 Register tmp = scope.AcquireX();
4853 Mov(dst.X(), src.D(), 1);
4854 Fmov(tmp.X(), src.D());
4855 Lsr(dst.X(), dst.X(), 62);
4856 Bfxil(dst.X(), tmp.X(), 63, 1);
4857}

4859void MacroAssembler::I64x2AllTrue(Register dst, VRegister src) {
4860 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(this);
4861 UseScratchRegisterScope scope(this);
4862 VRegister tmp = scope.AcquireV(kFormat2D);
4863 Cmeq(tmp.V2D(), src.V2D(), 0);
4864 Addp(tmp.D(), tmp);
4865 Fcmp(tmp.D(), tmp.D());
4866 Cset(dst, eq);
4867}
4868
4869// Calls an API function. Allocates HandleScope, extracts returned value
4870// from handle and propagates exceptions. Clobbers C argument registers
4871// and C caller-saved registers. Restores context. On return removes
4872// (*argc_operand + slots_to_drop_on_return) * kSystemPointerSize
4873// (GCed, includes the call JS arguments space and the additional space
4874// allocated for the fast call).
4875void CallApiFunctionAndReturn(MacroAssembler* masm, bool with_profiling,
4876 Register function_address,
4877 ExternalReference thunk_ref, Register thunk_arg,
4878 int slots_to_drop_on_return,
4879 MemOperand* argc_operand,
4880 MemOperand return_value_operand) {
4881 ASM_CODE_COMMENT(masm);
4882 ASM_LOCATION("CallApiFunctionAndReturn");
4883
4884 using ER = ExternalReference;
4885
4886 Isolate* isolate = masm->isolate();
4887 MemOperand next_mem_op = __ ExternalReferenceAsOperand(
4888 ER::handle_scope_next_address(isolate), no_reg);
4889 MemOperand limit_mem_op = __ ExternalReferenceAsOperand(
4890 ER::handle_scope_limit_address(isolate), no_reg);
4891 MemOperand level_mem_op = __ ExternalReferenceAsOperand(
4892 ER::handle_scope_level_address(isolate), no_reg);
4893
4894 Register return_value = x0;
4895 Register scratch = x4;
4896 Register scratch2 = x5;
4897
4898 // Allocate HandleScope in callee-saved registers.
4899 // We will need to restore the HandleScope after the call to the API function,
4900 // by allocating it in callee-saved registers it'll be preserved by C code.
4901 Register prev_next_address_reg = x19;
4902 Register prev_limit_reg = x20;
4903 Register prev_level_reg = w21;
4904
4905 // C arguments (kCArgRegs[0/1]) are expected to be initialized outside, so
4906 // this function must not corrupt them (return_value overlaps with
4907 // kCArgRegs[0] but that's ok because we start using it only after the C
4908 // call).
4909 DCHECK(!AreAliased(kCArgRegs[0], kCArgRegs[1], // C args
4910 scratch, scratch2, prev_next_address_reg, prev_limit_reg));
4911 // function_address and thunk_arg might overlap but this function must not
4912 // corrupted them until the call is made (i.e. overlap with return_value is
4913 // fine).
4914 DCHECK(!AreAliased(function_address, // incoming parameters
4915 scratch, scratch2, prev_next_address_reg, prev_limit_reg));
4916 DCHECK(!AreAliased(thunk_arg, // incoming parameters
4917 scratch, scratch2, prev_next_address_reg, prev_limit_reg));
4918
4919 // Explicitly include x16/x17 to let StoreReturnAddressAndCall() use them.
4920 UseScratchRegisterScope fix_temps(masm);
4921 fix_temps.Include(x16, x17);
4922
4923 {
4924 ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(masm,
4925 "Allocate HandleScope in callee-save registers.");
4926 __ Ldr(prev_next_address_reg, next_mem_op);
4927 __ Ldr(prev_limit_reg, limit_mem_op);
4928 __ Ldr(prev_level_reg, level_mem_op);
4929 __ Add(scratch.W(), prev_level_reg, 1);
4930 __ Str(scratch.W(), level_mem_op);
4931 }
4932
4933 Label profiler_or_side_effects_check_enabled, done_api_call;
4934 if (with_profiling) {
4935 __ RecordComment("Check if profiler or side effects check is enabled");
4936 __ Ldrb(scratch.W(),
4937 __ ExternalReferenceAsOperand(IsolateFieldId::kExecutionMode));
4938 __ Cbnz(scratch.W(), &profiler_or_side_effects_check_enabled);
4939#ifdef V8_RUNTIME_CALL_STATS
4940 __ RecordComment("Check if RCS is enabled");
4941 __ Mov(scratch, ER::address_of_runtime_stats_flag());
4942 __ Ldrsw(scratch.W(), MemOperand(scratch));
4943 __ Cbnz(scratch.W(), &profiler_or_side_effects_check_enabled);
4944#endif // V8_RUNTIME_CALL_STATS
4945 }
4946
4947 __ RecordComment("Call the api function directly.");
4948 __ StoreReturnAddressAndCall(function_address);
4949 __ Bind(&done_api_call);
4950
4951 Label propagate_exception;
4952 Label delete_allocated_handles;
4953 Label leave_exit_frame;
4954
4955 __ RecordComment("Load the value from ReturnValue");
4956 __ Ldr(return_value, return_value_operand);
4957
4958 {
4959 ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(
4960 masm,
4961 "No more valid handles (the result handle was the last one)."
4962 "Restore previous handle scope.");
4963 __ Str(prev_next_address_reg, next_mem_op);
4964 if (v8_flags.debug_code) {
4965 __ Ldr(scratch.W(), level_mem_op);
4966 __ Sub(scratch.W(), scratch.W(), 1);
4967 __ Cmp(scratch.W(), prev_level_reg);
4968 __ Check(eq, AbortReason::kUnexpectedLevelAfterReturnFromApiCall);
4969 }
4970 __ Str(prev_level_reg, level_mem_op);
4971
4972 __ Ldr(scratch, limit_mem_op);
4973 __ Cmp(prev_limit_reg, scratch);
4974 __ B(ne, &delete_allocated_handles);
4975 }
4976
4977 __ RecordComment("Leave the API exit frame.");
4978 __ Bind(&leave_exit_frame);
4979
4980 Register argc_reg = prev_limit_reg;
4981 if (argc_operand != nullptr) {
4982 // Load the number of stack slots to drop before LeaveExitFrame modifies sp.
4983 __ Ldr(argc_reg, *argc_operand);
4984 }
4985
4986 __ LeaveExitFrame(scratch, scratch2);
4987
4988 {
4989 ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(masm,
4990 "Check if the function scheduled an exception.");
4991 __ Mov(scratch, ER::exception_address(isolate));
4992 __ Ldr(scratch, MemOperand(scratch));
4993 __ JumpIfNotRoot(scratch, RootIndex::kTheHoleValue, &propagate_exception);
4994 }
4995
4996 __ AssertJSAny(return_value, scratch, scratch2,
4997 AbortReason::kAPICallReturnedInvalidObject);
4998
4999 if (argc_operand == nullptr) {
5000 DCHECK_NE(slots_to_drop_on_return, 0);
5001 __ DropSlots(slots_to_drop_on_return);
5002 } else {
5003 // {argc_operand} was loaded into {argc_reg} above.
5004 __ DropArguments(argc_reg, slots_to_drop_on_return);
5005 }
5006 __ Ret();
5007
5008 if (with_profiling) {
5009 ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(masm, "Call the api function via thunk wrapper.");
5010 __ Bind(&profiler_or_side_effects_check_enabled);
5011 // Additional parameter is the address of the actual callback function.
5012 if (thunk_arg.is_valid()) {
5013 MemOperand thunk_arg_mem_op = __ ExternalReferenceAsOperand(
5014 IsolateFieldId::kApiCallbackThunkArgument);
5015 __ Str(thunk_arg, thunk_arg_mem_op);
5016 }
5017 __ Mov(scratch, thunk_ref);
5018 __ StoreReturnAddressAndCall(scratch);
5019 __ B(&done_api_call);
5020 }
5021
5022 __ RecordComment("An exception was thrown. Propagate it.");
5023 __ Bind(&propagate_exception);
5024 __ TailCallRuntime(Runtime::kPropagateException);
5025
5026 {
5027 ASM_CODE_COMMENT_STRING(
5028 masm, "HandleScope limit has changed. Delete allocated extensions.");
5029 __ Bind(&delete_allocated_handles);
5030 __ Str(prev_limit_reg, limit_mem_op);
5031 // Save the return value in a callee-save register.
5032 Register saved_result = prev_limit_reg;
5033 __ Mov(saved_result, x0);
5034 __ Mov(kCArgRegs[0], ER::isolate_address());
5035 __ CallCFunction(ER::delete_handle_scope_extensions(), 1);
5036 __ Mov(kCArgRegs[0], saved_result);
5037 __ B(&leave_exit_frame);
5038 }
5039}
